# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ldap-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:ldap-protocol/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] An **authentication protocol** is a type of computer communications protocol or cryptographic protocol specifically designed for transfer of authentication data between two entities.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] It allows the receiving entity to authenticate the connecting entity (e.g.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Client connecting to a Server) as well as authenticate itself to the connecting entity (Server to a client) by declaring the type of information needed for authentication as well as syntax.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] It is the most important layer of protection needed for secure communication within computer networks.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] With the increasing amount of trustworthy information being accessible over the network, the need for keeping unauthorized persons from access to this data emerged.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] It is possible to steal one's identity in the computing world - special verification methods were invented to find out whether the person/computer requesting data is really who they say they are.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The task of the authentication protocol is to specify the exact series of steps needed for execution of the authentication.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] All the included parties have to follow the protocol.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] A protocol has to be unambiguous - each step must be defined precisely.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] A protocol must be complete - must include a specified action for every possible situation.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Alice (an entity wishing to be verified) and Bob (an entity verifying Alice's identity) are both aware of the protocol they agreed on using.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Bob has Alice's password stored in a database for comparison.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Bob checks the received password against the one stored in his database.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Then he sends a packet saying "Authentication successful" or "Authentication failed" based on the result.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] This is an example of a very basic authentication protocol vulnerable to many threats such as eavesdropping, replay attack, man-in-the-middle attacks, dictionary attacks or brute-force attacks.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Most authentication protocols are more complicated in order to be resilient against these attacks.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Protocols are used mainly by Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) servers to validate the identity of remote clients before granting them access to server data.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Most of them use a password as the cornerstone of the authentication.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] In most cases, the password has to be shared between the communicating entities in advance.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Password Authentication Protocol is one of the oldest authentication protocols.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Authentication is initialized by the client sending a packet with credentials (username and password) at the beginning of the connection, with the client repeating the authentication request until acknowledgement is received.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] It is highly insecure because credentials are sent "in the clear" and repeatedly, making it vulnerable even to the most simple attacks like eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle based attacks.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Although widely supported, it is specified that if an implementation offers a stronger authentication method, that method *must* be offered before PAP.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Mixed authentication (e.g. the same client alternately using both PAP and CHAP) is also not expected, as the CHAP authentication would be compromised by PAP sending the password in plain-text.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The authentication process in this protocol is always initiated by the server/host and can be performed anytime during the session, even repeatedly.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The server sends a random string (usually 128B long).
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The client uses the password and the string received as input to a hash function and then sends the result together with username in plain text.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The server uses the username to apply the same function and compares the calculated and received hash.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] An authentication is successful when the calculated and received hashes match.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] EAP was originally developed for PPP(Point-to-Point Protocol) but today is widely used in IEEE 802.3, IEEE 802.11(WiFi) or IEEE 802.16 as a part of IEEE 802.1x authentication framework.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The latest version is standardized in RFC 5247.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The advantage of EAP is that it is only a general authentication framework for client-server authentication - the specific way of authentication is defined in its many versions called EAP-methods.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Complex protocols used in larger networks for verifying the user (Authentication), controlling access to server data (Authorization) and monitoring network resources and information needed for billing of services (Accounting).
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The oldest AAA protocol using IP based authentication without any encryption (usernames and passwords were transported as plain text).
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Later version XTACACS (Extended TACACS) added authorization and accounting.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Both of these protocols were later replaced by TACACS+.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] TACACS+ separates the AAA components thus they can be segregated and handled on separate servers (It can even use another protocol for e.g.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] It uses TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) for transport and encrypts the whole packet.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service (RADIUS) is a full AAA protocol commonly used by Internet service providers.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Credentials are mostly username-password combination based, and it uses NAS and UDP protocol for transport.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Diameter (protocol) evolved from RADIUS and involves many improvements such as usage of more reliable TCP or SCTP transport protocol and higher security thanks to TLS.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Kerberos is a centralized network authentication system developed at MIT and available as a free implementation from MIT but also in many commercial products.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] It is the default authentication method in Windows 2000 and later.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] The authentication process itself is much more complicated than in the previous protocols - Kerberos uses symmetric key cryptography, requires a trusted third party and can use public-key cryptography during certain phases of authentication if need be.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Recent research in authentication protocols highlights advancements aimed at securing resource-constrained environments such as the Industrial Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] These modern protocols employ advanced cryptographic techniques, including Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC), to enable secure mutual authentication and session key agreement while minimizing computational and energy overhead.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Privacy-preserving mechanisms have also been integrated with biometric authentication to enhance security without compromising user confidentiality.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] Further emphasis has been placed on resistance to side-channel and replay attacks, alongside the achievement of forward and backward secrecy to protect session keys in dynamic network scenarios.
[src:ldap-protocol/authentication-protocol] These emerging technologies mark significant progress in making authentication more efficient and secure across evolving digital landscapes.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] In computing, a **directory service** or **name service** maps the names of network resources to their respective network addresses.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] It is a shared information infrastructure for locating, managing, administering and organizing everyday items and network resources, which can include volumes, folders, files, printers, users, groups, devices, telephone numbers and other objects.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] A directory service is a critical component of a network operating system.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] A **directory server** or name server is a server which provides such a service.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Each resource on the network is considered an object by the directory server.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Information about a particular resource is stored as a collection of attributes associated with that resource or object.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] A directory service defines a namespace for the network.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] The namespace is used to assign a *name* (unique identifier) to each of the objects.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Directories typically have a set of rules determining how network resources are named and identified, which usually includes a requirement that the identifiers be unique and unambiguous.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] When using a directory service, a user does not have to remember the physical address of a network resource; providing a name locates the resource.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Some directory services include access control provisions, limiting the availability of directory information to authorized users.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Several things distinguish a directory service from a relational database.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Attributes are sometimes multi-valued, allowing multiple naming attributes at one level (such as machine type and serial number concatenation, or multiple phone numbers for "work phone").
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Attributes and object classes are usually standardized throughout the industry; for example, X.500 attributes and classes are often formally registered with the IANA for their object ID.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Therefore, directory applications try to reuse standard classes and attributes to maximize the benefit of existing directory-server software.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Object instances are slotted into namespaces; each object class inherits from its parent object class (and ultimately from the root of the hierarchy), adding attributes to the must-may list.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Directory services are often central to the security design of an IT system and have a correspondingly-fine granularity of access control.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Replication and distribution have distinct meanings in the design and management of a directory service.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Replication is used to indicate that the same directory namespace (the same objects) are copied to another directory server for redundancy and throughput reasons; the replicated namespace is governed by the same authority.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Distribution is used to indicate that multiple directory servers in different namespaces are interconnected to form a distributed directory service; each namespace can be governed by a different authority.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Directory services were part of an Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) initiative for common network standards and multi-vendor interoperability.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] During the 1980s, the ITU and ISO created the X.500 set of standards for directory services, initially to support the requirements of inter-carrier electronic messaging and network-name lookup.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is based on the X.500 directory-information services, using the TCP/IP stack and an X.500 Directory Access Protocol (DAP) string-encoding scheme on the Internet.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Open-source tools to create directory services include OpenLDAP, the Kerberos protocol and Samba software, which can function as a Windows domain controller with Kerberos and LDAP back ends.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Administration is by GOsa or Samba SWAT.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Name services on Unix systems are typically configured through nsswitch.conf.
[src:ldap-protocol/directory-service] Information from name services can be retrieved with getent.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:ldap-protocol/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Despite its name, LDAP is much more than its protocol (i.e., much more than its HTTP API); it includes specifications of the required operation of systems satisfying its HTTP API and even specifies a standardized model of the data to be used by the HTTP API and managed by the directory service.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory services play an important role in developing intranet and Internet applications by allowing the sharing of information about users, systems, networks, services, and applications throughout the network.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As examples, directory services may provide any organized set of records, often with a hierarchical structure, such as a corporate email directory.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Similarly, a telephone directory is a list of subscribers with an address and a phone number.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common use of LDAP is to provide a central place to store usernames and passwords.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This allows many different applications and services to connect to the LDAP server to validate users.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP is a simpler (*lightweight*) subset of the standards in the X.500 series, particularly the X.511 Directory Access Protocol.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Because of this relationship, LDAP is sometimes called **X.500 Lite**.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Telecommunication companies' understanding of directory requirements were well developed after some 70 years of producing and managing telephone directories.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These companies introduced the concept of directory services to information technology and computer networking, their input culminating in the comprehensive X.500 specification, a suite of protocols produced by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) in the 1980s.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] X.500 directory services were traditionally accessed via the X.511 Directory Access Protocol (DAP), which required the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) protocol stack.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP was originally intended to be a lightweight alternative protocol for accessing X.500 directory services through the simpler (and now widespread) TCP/IP protocol stack.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This model of directory access was borrowed from the DIXIE and Directory Assistance Service protocols.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The protocol was originally created by Tim Howes of the University of Michigan, Steve Kille of Isode Limited, Colin Robbins of Nexor and Wengyik Yeong of Performance Systems International, circa 1993, as a successor to DIXIE and DAS.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Mark Wahl of Critical Angle Inc., Tim Howes, and Steve Kille started work in 1996 on a new version of LDAP, LDAPv3, under the aegis of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPv3, first published in 1997, superseded LDAPv2 and added support for extensibility, integrated the Simple Authentication and Security Layer, and better aligned the protocol to the 1993 edition of X.500.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Further development of the LDAPv3 specifications themselves and of numerous extensions adding features to LDAPv3 has come through the IETF.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the early engineering stages of LDAP, it was known as *Lightweight Directory Browsing Protocol*, or *LDBP*.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was renamed with the expansion of the scope of the protocol beyond directory browsing and searching, to include directory update functions.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was given its *Lightweight* name because it was not as network intensive as its DAP predecessor and thus was more easily implemented over the Internet due to its relatively modest bandwidth usage.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP has influenced subsequent Internet protocols, including later versions of X.500, XML Enabled Directory (XED), Directory Service Markup Language (DSML), Service Provisioning Markup Language (SPML), and the Service Location Protocol (SLP).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It is also used as the basis for Microsoft's Active Directory.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A client starts an LDAP session by connecting to an LDAP server, called a Directory System Agent (DSA), by default on TCP and UDP port 389, or on port 636 for LDAPS (LDAP over TLS/SSL, see below).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client then sends an operation request to the server, and a server sends responses in return.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] With some exceptions, the client does not need to wait for a response before sending the next request, and the server may send the responses in any order.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] All information is transmitted using Basic Encoding Rules (BER).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In addition the server may send "Unsolicited Notifications" that are not responses to any request, e.g. before the connection is timed out.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common alternative method of securing LDAP communication is using an SSL tunnel.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The default port for LDAP over SSL is 636.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The use of LDAP over SSL was common in LDAP Version 2 (LDAPv2) but it was never standardized in any formal specification.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This usage has been deprecated along with LDAPv2, which was officially retired in 2003.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A DN may change over the lifetime of the entry, for instance, when entries are moved within a tree.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To reliably and unambiguously identify entries, a UUID might be provided in the set of the entry's *operational attributes*.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`dn`" is the distinguished name of the entry; it is neither an attribute nor a part of the entry.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`cn=John Doe`" is the entry's RDN (Relative Distinguished Name), and "`dc=example,dc=com`" is the DN of the parent entry, where "`dc`" denotes 'Domain Component'.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The other lines show the attributes in the entry.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attribute names are typically mnemonic strings, like "`cn`" for common name, "`dc`" for domain component, "`mail`" for email address, and "`sn`" for surname.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A server holds a subtree starting from a specific entry, e.g.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers may also hold references to other servers, so an attempt to access "`ou=department,dc=example,dc=com`" could return a *referral* or *continuation reference* to a server that holds that part of the directory tree.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client can then contact the other server.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some servers also support *chaining*, which means the server contacts the other server and returns the results to the client.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP rarely defines any ordering: The server may return the values of an attribute, the attributes in an entry, and the entries found by a search operation in any order.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This follows from the formal definitions - an entry is defined as a set of attributes, and an attribute is a set of values, and sets need not be ordered.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The ADD operation inserts a new entry into the directory-server database.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the distinguished name in the add request already exists in the directory, then the server will not add a duplicate entry but will set the result code in the add result to decimal 68, "entryAlreadyExists".
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the above example, `uid=user,ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must not exist, and `ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must exist.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When an LDAP session is created, that is, when an LDAP client connects to the server, the **authentication state** of the session is set to anonymous.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The BIND operation establishes the authentication state for a session.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Simple BIND and SASL PLAIN can send the user's DN and password in plaintext, so the connections utilizing either Simple or SASL PLAIN should be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server typically checks the password against the `userPassword` attribute in the named entry.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Anonymous BIND (with empty DN and password) resets the connection to anonymous state.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] SASL (Simple Authentication and Security Layer) BIND provides authentication services through a wide range of mechanisms, e.g.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Kerberos or the client certificate sent with TLS.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND also sets the LDAP protocol version by sending a version number as an integer.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the client requests a version that the server does not support, the server must set the result code in the BIND response to the code for a protocol error.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Normally clients should use LDAPv3, which is the default in the protocol but not always in LDAP libraries.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND had to be the first operation in a session in LDAPv2, but is not required as of LDAPv3.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In LDAPv3, each successful BIND request changes the authentication state of the session and each unsuccessful BIND request resets the authentication state of the session.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an entry, an LDAP client transmits a properly formed delete request to the server.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Search operation is used to both search for and read entries.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name of the base object entry (or possibly the root) relative to which the search is to be performed.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] What elements below the baseObject to search.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] (the entire subtree starting at the base DN).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Criteria to use in selecting elements within scope.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] determine whether the values for those attributes match the filter assertion.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Note that a common misconception is that LDAP data is case-sensitive, whereas in fact matching rules and ordering rules determine matching, comparisons, and relative value relationships.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Which attributes to return in result entries.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Maximum number of entries to return, and maximum time to allow search to run.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These values, however, cannot override any restrictions the server places on size limit and time limit.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Return attribute types only, not attribute values.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server returns the matching entries and potentially continuation references.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The final result will include the result code.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Compare operation takes a DN, an attribute name and an attribute value, and checks if the named entry contains that attribute with that value.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation is used by LDAP clients to request that the LDAP server make changes to existing entries.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attempts to modify entries that do not exist will fail.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] MODIFY requests are subject to access controls as implemented by the server.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation requires that the distinguished name (DN) of the entry be specified, and a sequence of changes.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To replace the value of an existing attribute, use the `replace` keyword.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to update.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an attribute from an entry, use the keyword `delete` and the changetype designator `modify`.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to delete.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] There is also a Modify-Increment extension which allows an incrementable attribute value to be incremented by a specified amount.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When LDAP servers are in a replicated topology, LDAP clients should consider using the post-read control to verify updates instead of a search after an update.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The post-read control is designed so that applications need not issue a search request after an update – it is bad form to retrieve an entry for the sole purpose of checking that an update worked because of the replication eventual consistency model.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An LDAP client should not assume that it connects to the same directory server for each request because architects may have placed load-balancers or LDAP proxies or both between LDAP clients and servers.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Modify DN (move/rename entry) takes the new RDN (Relative Distinguished Name), optionally the new parent's DN, and a flag that indicates whether to delete the value(s) in the entry that match the old RDN.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server may support renaming of entire directory subtrees.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An update operation is atomic: Other operations will see either the new entry or the old one.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] On the other hand, LDAP does not define transactions of multiple operations: If you read an entry and then modify it, another client may have updated the entry in the meantime.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers may implement extensions that support this, though.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Extended Operation is a generic LDAP operation that can define new operations that were not part of the original protocol specification.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] StartTLS is one of the most significant extensions.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Other examples include Cancel and Password Modify.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The StartTLS operation establishes Transport Layer Security (the descendant of SSL) on the connection.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It can provide data confidentiality (to protect data from being observed by third parties) and/or data integrity protection (which protects the data from tampering).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] During TLS negotiation the server sends its X.509 certificate to prove its identity.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client may also send a certificate to prove its identity.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] After doing so, the client may then use SASL/EXTERNAL.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] By using the SASL/EXTERNAL, the client requests the server derive its identity from credentials provided at a lower level (such as TLS).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Though technically the server may use any identity information established at any lower level, typically the server will use the identity information established by TLS.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers also often support the non-standard "LDAPS" ("Secure LDAP", commonly known as "LDAP over SSL") protocol on a separate port, by default 636.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPS differs from LDAP in two ways: 1) upon connect, the client and server establish TLS before any LDAP messages are transferred (without a StartTLS operation) and 2) the LDAPS connection must be closed upon TLS closure.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some "LDAPS" client libraries only encrypt communication; they do not check the host name against the name in the supplied certificate.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Abandon operation requests that the server abort an operation named by a message ID.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Neither Abandon nor a successfully abandoned operation send a response.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A similar Cancel extended operation does send responses, but not all implementations support this.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Unbind operation abandons any outstanding operations and closes the connection.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name is of historical origin, and is *not* the opposite of the Bind operation.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients can abort a session by simply closing the connection, but they should use Unbind.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Unbind allows the server to gracefully close the connection and free resources that it would otherwise keep for some time until discovering the client had abandoned the connection.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It also instructs the server to cancel operations that can be canceled, and to not send responses for operations that cannot be canceled.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Most of the components described below are optional.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As in other URLs, special characters must be percent-encoded.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] There is a similar non-standard `ldaps` URI scheme for LDAP over SSL.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This should not be confused with LDAP with TLS, which is achieved using the StartTLS operation using the standard `ldap` scheme.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The contents of the entries in a subtree are governed by a directory schema, a set of definitions and constraints concerning the structure of the directory information tree (DIT).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The schema of a Directory Server defines a set of rules that govern the kinds of information that the server can hold.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attributes are the elements responsible for storing information in a directory, and the schema defines the rules for which attributes may be used in an entry, the kinds of values that those attributes may have, and how clients may interact with those values.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients may learn about the schema elements that the server supports by retrieving an appropriate subschema subentry.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Each entry must have an objectClass attribute, containing named classes defined in the schema.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The schema definition of the classes of an entry defines what kind of object the entry may represent - e.g. a person, organization or domain.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The object class definitions also define the list of attributes that must contain values and the list of attributes which may contain values.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, an entry representing a person might belong to the classes "top" and "person".
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Membership in the "person" class would require the entry to contain the "sn" and "cn" attributes, and allow the entry also to contain "userPassword", "telephoneNumber", and other attributes.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Since entries may have multiple ObjectClasses values, each entry has a complex of optional and mandatory attribute sets formed from the union of the object classes it represents.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] ObjectClasses can be inherited, and a single entry can have multiple ObjectClasses values that define the available and required attributes of the entry itself.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A parallel to the schema of an objectClass is a class definition and an instance in Object-oriented programming, representing LDAP objectClass and LDAP entry, respectively.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory servers may publish the directory schema controlling an entry at a base DN given by the entry's subschemaSubentry operational attribute.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Server administrators can add additional schema entries in addition to the provided schema elements.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A schema for representing individual people within organizations is termed a white pages schema.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP injection is a computer security attack similar to SQL injection that can occur when an application implementing LDAP fails to properly sanitize user input.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As an example, consider an LDAP search query that allows the user to search people by their name, the `cn` attribute.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A malicious user might replace a valid name with the `*` character, which matches any object with the `cn` attribute.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the application is vulnerable to this attack, it may display attributes that the searching user is not authorized to see.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP injection vulnerabilities are mitigated by escaping variables.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Escaping is accomplished with two distinct encoding functions — one for Distinguished Names and one for search strings — because they each allow different special characters.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some web frameworks come with escaping built in.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Like other parts of TCP/IP, LDAP was originally created without encryption.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This makes it vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks, in which attackers intercept credentials during the bind process.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This attack can be mitigated by requiring LDAPS or StartTLS during every bind involving credentials.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Much of the server operation is left to the implementor or administrator to decide.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Accordingly, servers may be set up to support a wide variety of scenarios.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, data storage in the server is not specified - the server may use flat files, databases, or just be a gateway to some other server.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Access control is not standardized, though there are commonly used models.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Users' passwords may be stored in their entries or elsewhere.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server may refuse to perform operations when it wishes, and impose various limits.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Examples: One can define new operations.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] *Controls* may modify requests and responses, e.g. to request sorted search results.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] New search scopes and Bind methods can be defined.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attributes can have *options* that may modify their semantics.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As LDAP has gained momentum, vendors have provided it as an access protocol to other services.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The implementation then recasts the data to mimic the LDAP/X.500 model, but how closely this model is followed varies.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, there is software to access SQL databases through LDAP, even though LDAP does not readily lend itself to this.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Similarly, data previously held in other types of data stores are sometimes moved to LDAP directories.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, Unix user and group information can be stored in LDAP and accessed via PAM and NSS modules.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP is often used by other services for authentication and/or authorization (what actions a given already-authenticated user can do on what service).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, in Active Directory Kerberos is used in the authentication step, while LDAP is used in the authorization step.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An example of such data model is the GLUE Schema, which is used in a distributed information system based on LDAP that enable users, applications and services to discover which services exist in a Grid infrastructure and further information about their structure and state.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An LDAP server may return referrals to other servers for requests that it cannot fulfill itself.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This requires a naming structure for LDAP entries so one can find a server holding a given distinguished name (DN), a concept defined in the X.500 Directory and also used in LDAP.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Another way of locating LDAP servers for an organization is a DNS server record (SRV).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An organization with the domain example.org may use the top level LDAP DN `dc=example, dc=org` (where *dc* means domain component).
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the LDAP server is also named ldap.example.org, the organization's top level LDAP URL becomes `ldap://ldap.example.org/dc=example,dc=org`.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Primarily two common styles of naming are used in both X.500 [2008] and LDAPv3.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These are documented in the ITU specifications and IETF RFCs.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The original form takes the top level object as the country object, such as `c=US`, `c=FR`.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The domain component model uses the model described above.
[src:ldap-protocol/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An example of country based naming could be `l=Locality, ou=Some Organizational Unit, o=Some Organization, c=FR`, or in the US: `cn=Common Name, l=Locality, ou=Some Organizational Unit, o=Some Organization, st=CA, c=US`.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Because these protocols used the OSI networking stack, a number of alternatives to DAP were developed to allow Internet clients to access the X.500 Directory using the TCP/IP networking stack.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The most well-known alternative to DAP is Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP).
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] While DAP and the other X.500 protocols can now use the TCP/IP networking stack, LDAP remains a popular directory access protocol.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The X.500 protocols traditionally use the OSI networking stack.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] However, the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) uses TCP/IP for transport.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] In later versions of the ITU Recommendation X.519, the Internet Directly-Mapped (IDM) protocols were introduced to allow X.500 protocol data units (PDUs) to be transported over the TCP/IP stack.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] This transport involves ISO Transport over TCP as well as a simple record-based binary protocol to frame protocol datagrams.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The primary concept of X.500 is that there is a single Directory Information Tree (DIT), a hierarchical organization of entries which are distributed across one or more servers, called Directory System Agents (DSA).
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] An entry consists of a set of attributes, each attribute with one or more values.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Each entry has a unique Distinguished Name, formed by combining its Relative Distinguished Name (RDN), one or more attributes of the entry itself, and the RDNs of each of the superior entries up to the root of the DIT.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] As LDAP implements a very similar data model to that of X.500, there is further description of the data model in the article on LDAP.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] X.520 and X.521 together provide a definition of a set of attributes and object classes to be used for representing people and organizations as entries in the DIT.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] They are one of the most widely deployed white pages schema.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] X.509, the portion of the standard providing for an authentication framework, is now also widely used outside of the X.500 directory protocols.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] It specifies a standard format for public-key certificates.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] X.509 was designed to be the secure access method for updating X.500 before the World Wide Web, but then as web browsers became popular, there needed to be a simple method of encrypting connections on the transport layer to web servers.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Hence, trusted root certificates for supported certificate authorities were pre-loaded into certificate storage areas on the communicating devices (e.g. personal computer, proxy, or web server).
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Added security is envisaged by the scheduled 2011-2014 implementation of the US National Strategy for Trusted Identities in Cyberspace, a two- to three-year project protecting digital identities in cyberspace.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The WWW e-commerce implementation of X.509v3 bypassed, but did not replace, the original ISO standard authentication mechanism of binding distinguished names in the X.500 Directory.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] These packages of certificates can be added or removed by the end user in their software, but are reviewed by browser and operating system vendors (such as Microsoft and Mozilla) in terms of their continued trustworthiness.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Should a problem arise, such as what occurred with DigiNotar, browser vendors can issue an update to mark a certificate authority as untrusted, but this is a serious removal effectively of that CA from "internet trust".
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] X.500 offers a way to view which organization claims a specific root certificate, outside of that provided bundle.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] This can function as a "4 corner model of trust" adding another check to determine if a root certificate has been compromised.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] For example, a web site using SSL, typically the DNS site name "www.foobar.com" is verified in a browser by the software using libraries that would check to see if the certificate was signed by one of the trusted root certificates given to the user.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Therefore, creating trust for users that they had reached the correct web site via HTTPS.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] However, stronger checks are also possible, to indicate that more than the domain name was verified.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] To contrast this with X.500, the certificate is one attribute of many for an entry, in which the entry could contain anything allowable by the specific Directory schema.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Thus X.500 does store the digital certificate, but it is one of many attributes that could potentially verify the organization, such as physical address, a contact telephone number and an email contact.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] This is in contrast with the Directory model which associates the attribute "caCertificate" with a listed certificate authority.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Thus the browser can verify the SSL cert of the website by means of the loaded group of accepted certificates or the root certificates can be looked up in an X.500 or LDAP Directory (or via HTTP/S) and imported into the list of trusted certificate authorities.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The "bound" distinguished name is located in the subject fields of the certificate which matches the Directory entry.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] X.509v3 can contain other extensions depending on the community of interest other than international domain names.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] For broad Internet use, RFC-5280 PKIX describes a profile for fields that may be useful for applications such as encrypted email.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The certificate itself is public and, because of its signature, considered to be unforgeable and can therefore be distributed in any manner, but an associated binding to an identity occurs in the Directory.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Binding is what links the certificate to the identity who claims to be using that certificate.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] For example, the X.500 software that runs the Federal Bridge has cross certificates that enable trust between certificate authorities.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] If a X.509v3 certificate is bound to a valid organization's distinguished name within the Directory, then a simple check can be made in regards to the authenticity of the certificate by a comparison with what is presented to the browser with what is present in the Directory.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Some options do exist to check notaries to see if a certificate has only recently been seen, and therefore more likely to have been compromised.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] If the cert is likely to be trusted and is failing because the domain name is a slight mismatch, it will then initially fail in the browser, but then be subjected to the notary trust, which can then bypass the browser warning.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] A valid organizational entry, such as o=FoobarWidgets, will also have an associated alphanumeric OID, and it has been "identity proofed" by ANSI, providing another layer of assurance regarding binding the certificate to the identity.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Some deployments (for example, the US Direct Project, which created standards for PKI in the healthcare industry) specify DNS-based publication of recipient S/MIME certificates, with options for DNS-based or LDAP-based discovery.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Early profiles used the DNS CERT Resource Record (RFC 4398); newer specifications define DANE mechanisms, including TLSA for TLS and SMIMEA for S/MIME.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] In practice, many production healthcare exchanges rely on curated trust-anchor bundles and directory/HTTP services, with DNSSEC/DANE adoption varying by ecosystem.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] DNS is sometimes preferred for storing and distributing information as it is highly available, and this can be applied to certificates and identities.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The concept of DNS root name servers has been contentious within the Internet community, though the issue is largely resolved for DNS.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] By contrast, the X.500 namespace has traditionally been viewed as starting with a national naming authority, mirroring ISO/ITU approaches with national representation.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Different countries therefore create their own unique X.500 services.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Events in 2011 highlighted threats from unknown nation-state actors forging certificates.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Similar techniques were used by Stuxnet to allow malicious software to impersonate trusted code – in that event, using stolen rather than forged certificates.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The aim of certificate transparency is to provide an end user with a simple procedure to determine whether a certificate is valid; checking only against the default bundle may be insufficient, hence the desire for an additional check.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] Other proposals for certificate transparency have also been advanced.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] A different attack affected Comodo, resulting in forged certificates targeting high-profile communications websites and necessitating urgent updates to major browsers.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] In that case, the certificates were actually issued by a trusted CA, leaving end users with no warning if they visited a spoofed site – unlike the Syrian incident, where the certificate was crudely forged (substituting "Alto Palo" for "Palo Alto") and contained incorrect serial numbers.
[src:ldap-protocol/x-500] The authors of RFC 2693 – "*SPKI Certificate Theory,*" note that "The original X.500 plan is unlikely ever to come to fruition.
